<p>IMO, the best way to start with Ohm-JS is by using the Ohm Editor.</p>

<p>I wrote a small intro to the Ohm Editor, and, I wrote down my train-of-thoughts as I learned Ohm-JS (I chose to transpile a Scheme library to JS to get a js-prolog).</p>

<p><a href="https://guitarvydas.github.io/2021/05/09/Ohm-Editor.html">Ohm Editor</a><br />
<a href="https://guitarvydas.github.io/2020/12/09/OhmInSmallSteps.html">Ohm In Small Steps</a></p>

<p>I wrote these a long time ago and my writing style has changed (I hope that it has become ‚Äúsimpler‚Äù).</p>

<p>IMO, the best way to develop a language is:<br />
1) create the grammar with the Ohm-Editor<br />
1a) Test the grammar using the Ohm-Editor and various language snippets.<br />
2) Write an identity transform (input-&gt;parser-&gt;output, same output as input).<br />
3) Modify the identity transform to suit your needs.</p>

<p>I modified the sample Ohm grammar (Arithmetic) to create transpilers for WASM, Python, JS and Lisp:</p>

<p><a href="https://guitarvydas.github.io/2021/05/15/WASM-Arithmetic-Transpiler.html">WASM Prototype</a></p>

<p><a href="https://guitarvydas.github.io/2021/05/11/Ohm-Arithmetic.html">Python, JS, Lisp Prototypes</a></p>

